<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,440,1008]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,307,440,467]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Distribution:</emphasis>
This species is endemic to 
<collectingCountry box="[627,723,441,467]" name="Turkey" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Krauss, H." box="[741,889,441,467]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" pagination="57 - 64" refId="ref12062" refString="Krauss, H. (1879) Synonymische Bemerkungen mit Bezug auf Bolivar's Catalogus Orth. Opterorum Europae. Verhandlungen der Zoologisch-Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 29, 57 - 64." type="journal article" year="1879">Krauss 1879</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kirby, W. F." box="[903,1037,441,467]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" refId="ref11824" refString="Kirby, W. F. (1906) Orthoptera Saltatoria. Part I. (Achetidae et Phasgonuridae). A Synonymic Catalogue of Orthoptera (Orthoptera Saltatoria, Locustidae vel Acridiidae). British Museum (Natural History), London, 562 pp." type="book" year="1906">Kirby 1906</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kaltenbach, A." box="[1051,1247,441,467]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" pagination="68 - 82" refId="ref11407" refString="Kaltenbach, A. (1964) Zur Systematik und Verbreitung der Raubheuschrecken (Tettigoniidae - Saginae), insbesondere der europaischen Arten der Gattung Saga Charpentier, Zeitschrift der Arbeitsgemeinschaft Osterreichischer Entomologen, 16, 68 - 82" type="journal article" year="1964">Kaltenbach 1964</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Kaltenbach, A." box="[1260,1320,441,468]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" pagination="3 - 107" refId="ref11446" refString="Kaltenbach, A. (1967) Unterlagen fur eine Monographie der Saginae I. Superrevision der Gattung Saga Charpentier (Saltatoria: Tettigoniidae), Beitrage zur Entomologie, 17, 3 - 107." type="journal article" year="1967">1967</bibRefCitation>
). The distribution of species in 
<collectingCountry box="[404,500,477,503]" name="Turkey" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Anatolia</collectingCountry>
is concentrated mostly in Mediterranean and South-Eastern parts (
<figureCitation box="[1255,1373,477,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1744,1769]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,1034,1719]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,1021,1725]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution map (A) and male calling song of Saga longicaudata (B—phrase series, C—one complete phrase and D—a group of syllables, black arrow is the hypothetic opening hemisyllable movement and grey arrow is the hypothetic closing hemisyllable movement)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3383546/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Figure 4A</figureCitation>
) of it (
<bibRefCitation author="Ramme, W." box="[159,314,512,539]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" pagination="260 - 343" refId="ref12291" refString="Ramme, W. (1951) Zur systematik, Faunistik und Biologie der Orthopteren von Sudost-Europa und Vorderasien. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum Berlin, 27, 260 - 343. https: // doi. org / 10.1002 / mmnz. 4830270108" type="journal article" year="1951">Ramme 1951</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kaltenbach, A." box="[325,520,513,540]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" pagination="3 - 107" refId="ref11446" refString="Kaltenbach, A. (1967) Unterlagen fur eine Monographie der Saginae I. Superrevision der Gattung Saga Charpentier (Saltatoria: Tettigoniidae), Beitrage zur Entomologie, 17, 3 - 107." type="journal article" year="1967">Kaltenbach 1967</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,440,1008]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,390,548,575]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Song recording:</emphasis>
Male specimens are collected from 
<collectingCountry box="[792,873,549,575]" name="Turkey" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Turkey</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[882,958,549,575]" country="Turkey" name="Adana" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Adana</collectingRegion>
, Saimbeyli, Obruk plateau, Saksağan Pass, 
<geoCoordinate box="[151,293,584,611]" degrees="38" direction="north" minutes="03.57" orientation="latitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="9" value="38.0595">N 38°03.57’</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[305,457,584,611]" degrees="036" direction="east" minutes="06.59" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="9" value="36.109833">E 036°06.59’</geoCoordinate>
, 
<quantity box="[470,557,585,611]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.678" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" unit="m" value="1678.0">1678 m</quantity>
, 
<date box="[570,709,584,611]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" value="2015-07-09">09.VII.2015</date>
, leg.: D. Sirin, A. Mol &amp; M. S. Taylan, and the calling songs are recorded from two males at 30 ˚C in the laboratory conditions (by D. Şirin).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,440,1008]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,440,656,683]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Description of song:</emphasis>
Totally 12 records from two males were examined. The calling song consists of phrases (
<figureCitation box="[159,275,693,719]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1744,1769]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,1034,1719]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,1021,1725]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution map (A) and male calling song of Saga longicaudata (B—phrase series, C—one complete phrase and D—a group of syllables, black arrow is the hypothetic opening hemisyllable movement and grey arrow is the hypothetic closing hemisyllable movement)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3383546/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Figure 4B</figureCitation>
) with irregular intervals. Phrase durations vary between 0.93 and 1.07 s (1.01 ± 0.04), and each phrase contains 31–37 syllables (33.3 ± 1.5). The phrase generally begins with an isolated 
<emphasis box="[1068,1261,729,755]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">first hemisyllable</emphasis>
and is followed by a gap which lasts for 8–19 ms (13.6± 3.6). After the gap, the phrase continues with 2–3 higher amplitude syllable group and a 2–4 lower amplitude syllable group (generally corresponds to 1/8 of phrase), then reaches the highest amplitude after this part and goes along with ordinary syllables which have a quite similar amplitude (
<figureCitation box="[1292,1374,837,863]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1744,1769]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,1034,1719]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,1021,1725]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution map (A) and male calling song of Saga longicaudata (B—phrase series, C—one complete phrase and D—a group of syllables, black arrow is the hypothetic opening hemisyllable movement and grey arrow is the hypothetic closing hemisyllable movement)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3383546/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Fig 4C</figureCitation>
). The oscillographic analyses show that the syllable periods duration varies between 21.20 and 38.21 ms (26.35 ± 1.98), and each syllable shows a standard structure, which is formulated as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">soft and long opening hemisyllable + loud and short closing hemisyllable</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[462,583,945,971]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1744,1769]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,1034,1719]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,1021,1725]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Distribution map (A) and male calling song of Saga longicaudata (B—phrase series, C—one complete phrase and D—a group of syllables, black arrow is the hypothetic opening hemisyllable movement and grey arrow is the hypothetic closing hemisyllable movement)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3383546/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Figure 4D</figureCitation>
). The opening hemisyllables duration varies between 7.59–21.46 ms (16.39 ± 1.82), while the closing hemisyllable lasts for 6.80–17.53 ms (9.96 ± 1.46).
</paragraph>
